Data

  • Simulated data from Coxe, S., West, S. G., & Aiken, L. S. (2009). The analysis of count data: A gentle introduction to Poisson regression and its alternatives. Journal of Personality Assessment, 91(2), 121-136.
    • case: Subject ID
    • sensation: Sensation seeking (1 to 7)
    • gender: 0 = female, 1 = male
    • y: Number of alcoholic beverages consumed on Saturday night

sensation predicts y

Scatterplot of y vs sensation

  • The options in geom_smooth() tell it to fit a Poisson regression curve
    • method = "glm" : use a generalized linear model
    • method.args = list(family = "poisson") : specifically, use a Poisson regression (i.e., count outcome)
ggplot(data = jpa, aes(x = sensation, y = y)) + 
    geom_point(alpha = 0.2, size = 5) +
    geom_smooth(method = "glm", 
                method.args = list(family = "poisson"), 
                se = TRUE)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Poisson regression model

  • sensation4 is centered at 4 (the midpoint of the 1 to 7 scale)
  • glm() works very much like lm()
    • Additional options specify the type of GLiM
      • Here, Poisson regression (with Poisson outcome distribution and log link function) is specified by family = poisson(link = "log")
jpa <- jpa %>% mutate(sensation4 = sensation - 4)
alc_sens4_poi <- glm(y ~ sensation4, 
                     data = jpa, 
                     family = poisson(link = "log"))

summary() of the model

Overdispersed Poisson regression

  • sensation4 is centered at 4 (the midpoint of the 1 to 7 scale)
  • glm() works very much like lm()
    • Additional options specify the type of GLiM
      • Here, overdispersed Poisson regression (with quasi Poisson outcome distribution and log link function) is specified by family = quasipoisson(link = "log")
alc_sens4_odpoi <- glm(y ~ sensation4, 
                       data = jpa, 
                       family = quasipoisson(link = "log"))

Overdispersion

  • You can print the overdispersion parameter (\(\psi\)) using
psi_odpoi <- summary(alc_sens4_odpoi)$dispersion
psi_odpoi
[1] 2.847168
  • If there is overdispersion, the \(\psi\) value will be greater than 1

Negative binomial regression

  • sensation4 is centered at 4 (the midpoint of the 1 to 7 scale)
  • Negative binomial regression uses the glm.nb() function from the MASS package
    • It also works similarly to lm()
    • Specify data
    • Specify outcome ~ predictor relationship
alc_sens4_nb <- glm.nb(data = jpa, 
                       y ~ sensation4)

Overdispersion

  • You can print the overdispersion parameter (\(\theta = \frac{1}{\alpha}\)) using
theta_nb <- summary(alc_sens4_nb)$theta
theta_nb
[1] 1.392859
alpha_nb <- 1 / theta_nb
alpha_nb
[1] 0.7179475
  • If there is overdispersion, the \(\alpha\) value will be greater than 0

Interpretation

  • This is the interpretation for the Poisson and overdispersed Poisson models
    • The logic for negative binomial regression interpretation is the same, but the actual numbers will be different

Intercept

  • Predicted count of alcoholic drinks (y) when sensation seeking = 4 (sensation4 = 0)

    • \(\hat{Y} = \hat{\mu} = e^{b_0}\) =
count_X0_poi <- exp(sens4_b0_poi) 
count_X0_poi
[1] 2.193729

  • A person with sensation4 = 0 (sensation = 4) is predicted to drink 2.19 alcoholic drinks

  • You can also convert it to the natural log of the predicted count metric:

log_X0_poi <- log(count_X0_poi)
log_X0_poi
[1] 0.785603
  • The natural log of the predicted number of drinks for a person with sensation4 = 0 (sensation = 4) is 0.79

Slope

  • From the slope, you can calculate the rate ratio (RR)
RR <- exp(sens4_b1_poi) 
RR
[1] 1.260465
  • The rate ratio is the multiplicative change in the predicted count for a 1 unit change in the predictor
    • Constant multiplicative change
    • For every 1 unit increase in sensation4, we expect the predicted count to get multiplied by 1.26
    • You can also interpret this as a \(26\) percent increase

Predicted values

  • This is just one way to do this that I find the easiest
    • Grab the \(b_0\) and \(b_1\) values from the output
      • We already saved these above as variables: sens4_b0_poi and sens4_b1_poi for Poisson regression, etc.
    • Create some X values that correspond to the predictor
      • sensation ranges from \(1\) to \(7\) (in theory)
      • sensation4 ranges from \(-3\) to \(3\) (in theory)
      • Donât include too many values or the table will get too large
    • Calculate the predicted count using the equations from lecture
    • Combine all the variables into a data frame
x <- c(-3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3)
pred_count_poi <- exp(sens4_b0_poi + sens4_b1_poi * x) 
pred_count_odpoi <- exp(sens4_b0_odpoi + sens4_b1_odpoi * x) 
pred_count_nb <- exp(sens4_b0_nb + sens4_b1_nb * x) 
predicted <- data.frame(x, pred_count_poi, pred_count_odpoi, pred_count_nb)
  • If youâre using markdown or Quarto with R, you can print the table in HTML with formatting to look nicer and be a bit easier to read
knitr::kable(predicted, digits = 2, row.names = F)

  • Plot the regression lines
    • Iâm only including the Poisson and negative binomial models because the overdispersed Poisson model is the same as the Poisson model

Plot of predicted probability values

  • Some code adapted from the Atkins & Gallop (2007) article (Figure 1)
    • predprob() function from pscl package calculates predicted probabilities of count values based on the model
      • Predicted probability of each outcome value for each person
        • Not just the personâs predicted value
      • Then take the mean for each outcome value (column) using apply()
        • The 2 tells it to get the mean for each column
        • One predicted probability for each value of the outcome
      • Put those in a dataset with the possible outcome values (0 to 17)
phat.pois <- predprob(alc_sens4_poi)
phat.pois.mn <- apply(phat.pois, 2, mean)
phat.pois.mn
